### Lambda Expressions

Lambdas are anonymous function objects that can be defined inline. Introduced in C++11 with improvements in C++14, C++17, and C++20.

---

### Syntax

```cpp
[capture](parameters) -> return_type {
  // Function body
};
```

---

### Basic Examples

```cpp
auto square = [](int x) { return x * x; };
cout << square(5);  // 25

auto add = [](int a, int b) -> int {
  return a + b;
};
```

---

### Capture Clause

| Capture | Description |
|---------|-------------|
| `[]` | Nothing captured |
| `[x]` | Capture x by value |
| `[&x]` | Capture x by reference |
| `[=]` | All variables by value |
| `[&]` | All variables by reference |
| `[=, &x]` | All by value, x by reference |
| `[this]` | Capture this pointer |

---

### Capture Example

```cpp
int factor = 10;
auto multiply = [factor](int x) { return x * factor; };
cout << multiply(5);  // 50

int sum = 0;
auto addToSum = [&sum](int x) { sum += x; };
addToSum(5);
addToSum(10);
cout << sum;  // 15
```

---

### Generic Lambdas (C++14)

```cpp
auto print = [](const auto& value) {
  cout << value << endl;
};

print(42);       // int
print("hello");  // const char*
```

---

> **Key Point:** Lambdas are widely used with STL algorithms like `std::sort`, `std::for_each`, and `std::find_if`. They improve code readability by keeping logic close to where it is used.

codeExample:
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
#include <algorithm>
using namespace std;

int main() {
  vector<int> nums = {5, 2, 8, 1, 9};

  sort(nums.begin(), nums.end(), [](int a, int b) {
    return a > b;  // Sort descending
  });

  for (int n : nums) {
    cout << n << " ";
  }
  return 0;
}
